North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that last year North Korea took “essential measures out of goodwill,” for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and committing to not multiplying nuclear weapons and technologies.
“We don’t see a response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri relied on North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, which would reward North Korea for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which he pledged to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes calls for a loosening of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and is even against the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to our knees is a whim of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not respond to plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the denuclearization issue instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to a standstill.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris’ speech differed enormously from his speech last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the mainland of the United States with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened North Korea's "complete destruction" last year, overcrowded Kim at the United Nations with praise for his courage in disarmament steps, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea's denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “Enforcement of Security Council sanctions must definitely continue vigorously until we have reached complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry up Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
