Harvard Students Learn to Sleep Enough in a Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all elementary school students get more sleep this year, a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often needless when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and in his opinion is the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the day, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
"No one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the picture of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
Subsequently, they are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine using a map of the university grounds with interactive symbols.
“We know that it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this – just like you have a right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” Czeisler said.
The pride in pushing a “night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring enough good sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and fears, he said, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, who had taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar program of study before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler, students should set up an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the damaging effects of “blue light” emanating from electronic screens and LED lighting, which can get the circadian rhythm off the beat, leading to problems with falling asleep.
