The Global Citizen Festival, which was first held in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international stakeholder group that seeks to fight poverty by motivating more and more people to participate actively in the fight against poverty.
To get a free ticket for the event (the other option would be to buy a VIP ticket), you need to complete a number of tasks, including volunteering, communicating with a leading politician worldwide (via email or phone) or similar measures to raise awareness of the goal – fighting poverty.
How successful is the project when you consider that Global Citizen has 12 years left to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of putting forward a cool free concert a meaningful way to convince others that it’s time to act, or just another case of so-called clicktivism – if you think you’re going to change something by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen said that since 2011, the project has achieved more than 19 million actions by its supporters and has achieved various goals.
These actions are said to have helped inspire leaders around the world to announce commitments and strategies worth more than $37 billion that will impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from its actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid out or raised through fundraising.
According to the group’s estimates, the funds secured so far have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of UK-based investors and implementers who have pledged to support children in their optimal development and who have promised to help Rwanda fight malnutrition in the country with $35 million, after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition a footnote in history,” The Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told the audience during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions calling for the UK to improve the nutritional situation of mothers and children, the government announced funding for the Power of Nutrition project, which aims to reach 5 million women and children and provides nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the website, namely, what are the reasons why Global Citizen can fight extreme poverty,
They replied, “It will be a long and strenuous journey with ups and downs.
But similar to the big civil rights and anti-apartheid movements ahead of us, we will succeed as we are stronger and more influential together.
