The inventor of the World Wide Web plans the launch of a new Internet to counter Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is currently launching a startup with the aim of establishing a competition with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The technology legend’s latest project, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s Solid open source platform.
With Solid, users can choose where their data is stored and who gets access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee said that the intention behind Inrupt was "world domination".
“We need to be active now,” he said about startup.
“This is an historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology so users can create their own personal online data store or POD.
It can include contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library, and other tools for the private and corporate sectors.
Similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, all content is available in one browser and at the same time.
The special thing about personal online data storage is that the user can decide who can access which data.
The company describes this concept as personal empowerment and development through data.
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company deploys resources, processes, and related skills to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a few developers who have been hired to work on this project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to build their own decentralized apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
