These data will help to determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and show how to preserve forested areas for bats and other related species.
Bat stocks in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affect sleeping places and lead to habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also be a risk, as can fly catchers and chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their ears are more useful than their eyes because of their nocturnal hunting habits when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS responsible for maintaining over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland takes the subject of bats very seriously.
