“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there's a lot we don't know about bats yet, so we're doing this work here and on other goods that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stresses the importance of initially excluding bats from being present before maintenance work on the goods, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single nesting place could kill up to 400 females and young animals and exterminate the entire population on site.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
