Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of income for the economy of Central Sulawesi, especially the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but it focuses mainly on Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been victims of earthquakes and tsunamis several times over the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Civil Protection Agency.
In 1938, more than 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, Donggala was hit by a tsunami that killed nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire, and is regularly plagued by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A powerful earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami on December 26 that struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people in the coastal areas of the Indian Ocean, almost half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias islands off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake of magnitude 6.8 rocked southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast and claimed nearly 700 lives.
2009: An earthquake of 7.6 struck the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake of magnitude 7.5 rocked one of the Mentawai islands off Sumatra, triggering a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and claimed about 300 lives.
2016: A slight earthquake shook the Pidie Jaya government district in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly earthquake and tsunamis of 2004.
