However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, sank his tee in the water on the 16th lane (par 3) and lost to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europa, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the best ranking in the world, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, a veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I am so happy to win the cup back.
It’s about the team and I’m happy to have contributed,” said the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He continues the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against the American golf legend Tiger Woods in the singles on Sunday 2:1.
I’m so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, who I’ve been chasing on television since childhood.”
Woods lost all of his four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup score of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA struggled to find the fairways all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who have delivered high-profile performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the guys, they fought.
There was a time this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We didn't make any of it.
Hat off for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players performed well.
We’re going to regroup, I’m going to talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we’re going to look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their captain.
You have to take off the hat.
We were defeated.”
Red tide update: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are declining
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more gaping flowering conditions are recorded in the areas of the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae bloom stretches over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee District.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer spots compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the last week, medium concentrations in or off the coast of the Pinellas District were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Manatee District, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Charlotte District, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Lee District, and low concentrations in the Collier District.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
No new respiratory problems have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
